<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=VC8wAQAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA69&amp;lpg=PA69" rel="nofollow">books.google.com/books?id=VC8wAQAAMAAJ&amp;pg=PA69&amp;lp...</a>
mentions the introduction of skating exhibitions at the Hippodrome [<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Hippodrome" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Hippodrome</a>] in an article entitled &quot;A Country Sport in City Clothes.&quot;

The  <a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn88086023/1916-12-01/ed-1/seq-5/" rel="nofollow">East Oregonian, December 01, 1916, DAILY EVENING EDITION, Image 5</a> used this photo with the caption &quot;GENERAL TREPOFF BECOMES PREMIER - LONDON, Dec 1.- Dispatches from Petrograd today announce the retirement of M. Strumer, premier of Russia, and the assumption of the office by his successor, General Alexander Trepoff. ...&quot;

But according to wikipedia, the photo shows Dmitri Feodorovich Trepov, who died in 1906 (<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dmitri_Feodorovich_Trepov" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dmitri_Feodorovich_Trepov</a>).

Alexander Trepov would be this man: <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Trepov" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexander_Trepov</a>

A photo of the Countess de Montagnac, taken obviously at the same occasion, is in  <a href="http://oregonnews.uoregon.edu/lccn/sn83045782/1916-12-10/ed-1/seq-67/" rel="nofollow">The Sunday Oregonian, December 10, 1916, SECTION FIVE, Image 67</a> with the caption:
&quot;THE Countess de Montagnac has come to America to raise money for the war widows of France. She has brought with her a collection of rare laces contributed by French women to sell for their benefit.&quot;

On the same page is a photo of Winifred Holt with the caption:
&quot;Winifred Holt, a New York woman has returned from Paris to raise money for the support of the &quot;Phare de France&quot; or &quot;Lighthouse&quot; for the blind, which she established there. Since the beginning of the war the &quot;Lighthouses&quot; at Paris, Bordeaux and other cities established under the plans of Miss Holt have cared for 300 blind and 3000 partly blind French soldiers.&quot;

The bird at top left (and in the 1901 bookplate at the Pratt Institute) might well the the Passenger Pigeon, which had been in dramatic decline in the 1890s and was extinct by 1924 (the date on this bookplate).  See for example, in <a href="http://www.audubonmagazine.org/articles/birds/why-passenger-pigeon-went-extinct" rel="nofollow">www.audubonmagazine.org/articles/birds/why-passenger-pige...</a>
&quot;In 1871 their great communal nesting sites had covered 850 square miles of Wisconsin's sandy oak barrens--136 million breeding adults, naturalist A.W. Schorger later estimated. After that the population plummeted until, by the mid-1890s, wild flock sizes numbered in the dozens rather than the hundreds of millions (or even billions). Then they disappeared altogether, except for three captive breeding flocks spread across the Midwest. About September 1, 1914, the last known passenger pigeon, a female named Martha, died at the Cincinnati Zoo. &quot;

If the left-hand bird is a Passenger Pigeon, the right-hand one might be a Great Auk, which became extinct in the mid-19th century according to <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_auk" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_auk</a>

Possibly <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adriano_Hernandez" rel="nofollow">en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adriano_Hernandez</a>
