A 1921 article entitled &quot;Churches and Red Propaganda&quot; described it this way: &quot;A typical example of the use made of the Presbyterian Church by radical and revolutionary groups is to be found in the Labor Temple at Fourteenth Street and Second Avenue in the Borough of Manhattan City of New York. In this center there has been organized a regularly constituted Presbyterian Church known as the American International Church at which certain Church services are held. It appears from investigation that the neighborhood served by this organization is made up largely of foreigners from different lands of radical and revolutionary tendencies. Those in charge, apparently feeling the necessity of reaching the unchurched, have deemed it expedient to open the Church building during the past year freely to those who wish to spread revolutionary and subversive doctrines. An examination of the advertised meetings held at this center discloses that the vast majority of the speakers have been identified with one or another of the radical or revolutionary groups.&quot;
<a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=5SIoAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=RA1-PA19&amp;lpg=RA1-PA19&amp;dq=american+international+church,+labor+temple,+new+york&amp;source=bl&amp;ots=T9TMF5s_o0&amp;sig=xSa5TC4RKEVajtodJoNk1VXWT6Q&amp;hl=en&amp;sa=X&amp;ei=6CLuU_WhDcHyiwLomYGAAQ&amp;ved=0CFMQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&amp;q=american international church, labor temple, new york&amp;f=false" rel="nofollow">books.google.com/books?id=5SIoAAAAYAAJ&amp;pg=RA1-PA19&amp;am...</a>

